    correctOptionId: 'a',
    explanation: "Bedrock Flows Condition nodes evaluate one or more boolean conditions against the input and route execution to different downstream paths. This enables branching pipelines where document type, content flags, or other attributes determine which processing path is followed. ✓ (a) The Condition node is the native Bedrock Flows branching mechanism: it evaluates boolean expressions on the flow\'s input data (e.g., documentType == \"invoice\") and routes execution to the matching downstream branch. ✗ (b) The Iterator node loops over array inputs and passes each element to a downstream sub-flow sequentially; it does not evaluate conditions or branch execution based on document attributes — it is for fan-out iteration, not conditional routing. ✗ (c) A Lambda node executes a custom function and can return a value, but Lambda nodes themselves do not perform flow-level branching; conditional routing between downstream nodes is done by a Condition node that may use a Lambda node\'s output as its input. ✗ (d) A Prompt node invokes a foundation model and returns generated text; while an FM could classify document types in natural language, the output would need to feed into a Condition node for actual flow branching — a Prompt node alone cannot route execution to different downstream paths.",
