    explanation: "Streaming (InvokeModelWithResponseStream) returns response tokens as they are generated. For long-document tasks, this dramatically reduces perceived latency because the user/application receives output immediately rather than waiting for the complete 120K-token-input computation to finish before any output is returned. ✓ (a) InvokeModelWithResponseStream begins delivering generated tokens to the client as soon as the first output token is produced; editors see the summary start appearing immediately rather than waiting for the full response to be buffered and returned. ✗ (b) The Batch Inference API is an asynchronous, offline processing mode designed for large-scale non-interactive workloads; it does not support real-time streaming and adds significant latency as results are stored to S3 and polled, making it the worst choice when editors need results in real time. ✗ (c) Compressing the document with gzip reduces payload transmission time over the network by a small amount, but the dominant latency for a 120,000-token input is model computation time — gzip compression does not change how many tokens the model must process or when the first output token is generated. ✗ (d) Splitting into 10K token chunks and summarising in parallel reduces total computation time but produces fragmented partial summaries that must then be merged with a second model call; this increases total latency and complexity, and does not minimise time-to-first-token for editors reviewing a coherent summary.",
